    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Car Depreciation Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Our car depreciation calculator uses the declining balance method to estimate your vehicle's value over time. Enter your vehicle's purchase price, its current age, the expected annual depreciation rate, and how many years you plan to keep it. The calculator generates a year-by-year schedule showing exactly how value declines, plus summary figures for current value, future value, and total depreciation during the holding period.
      </p>
      <p>
        The default 15% annual rate after year one is a widely-used industry average, though your actual depreciation may differ based on make, model, mileage, condition, and market demand. New vehicles use a 20% first-year depreciation rate to reflect the well-documented steep initial drop in value.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Car Depreciation</h2>
      <p>
        Depreciation is the single largest cost of vehicle ownership for most drivers, often exceeding fuel, insurance, and maintenance costs combined. A $35,000 new car will typically lose over $15,000 in value during its first three years. Understanding depreciation helps you make smarter buying and selling decisions, whether you are purchasing new or used, deciding between leasing and buying, or timing a sale.
      </p>

      <h3>The Depreciation Curve</h3>
      <p>
        Cars depreciate fastest in the first three years. A new car loses roughly 20% of its value the moment you drive it off the lot, then continues to lose 15% annually. By year five, it retains only about 37% of its original value. After five years, the rate slows significantly, and by year ten, values stabilize. This is why buying a 2-3 year old vehicle is often the best financial decision, as someone else absorbs the steepest depreciation.
      </p>

      <h3>Factors That Influence Depreciation Rate</h3>
      <p>
        Brand reputation, reliability scores, fuel economy, market demand, and body style all influence how quickly a vehicle loses value. Trucks and SUVs typically depreciate more slowly than sedans. Popular models with strong reliability records, like Toyota and Lexus, hold value better than luxury European brands. Color, options, and condition at time of sale also play a role.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How fast do cars depreciate?</h3>
      <p>
        New cars depreciate fastest in the first year, losing approximately 20% of their value. After that, vehicles typically lose 15% per year for the next several years. By year five, a new car is worth roughly 37-40% of its original purchase price.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the declining balance depreciation method?</h3>
      <p>
        The declining balance method calculates depreciation as a fixed percentage of the vehicle's current value each year rather than its original price. The dollar amount decreases each year even though the rate stays the same, accurately reflecting how cars lose more value in earlier years.
      </p>

      <h3>Which cars hold their value best?</h3>
      <p>
        Trucks and SUVs generally hold their value best, especially Toyota, Lexus, and Porsche vehicles. The Toyota Tacoma, Jeep Wrangler, and Porsche 911 consistently rank among the lowest-depreciating vehicles.
      </p>

      <h3>Does mileage affect car depreciation?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, mileage is one of the largest factors in car depreciation beyond age. Cars with significantly higher mileage depreciate faster, while low-mileage vehicles retain more value.
      </p>

      <h3>How can I minimize car depreciation?</h3>
      <p>
        Buy a car that is 2-3 years old, keep mileage reasonable, maintain the vehicle well with documented service records, choose popular colors and common options, and avoid modifications. Selling privately rather than trading in also helps you recover more value.
      </p>

    <%= render "shared/print_button" %>
    <%= render "shared/calculation_email_capture" %>
</article>

